<span id="freeTextContainer6503701414807458456">A book about books. A reading about readings. As a book-lover from a young age, I had only ever thought of reading as leisure and never as a discipline. I now see it as both—or, as Reinke puts it, a difficult pleasure. Who would have thought that there could be strategies to becoming a better reader? Not me! But Lit! contains some definitive, actionable tips. One chapter , for example, is devoted to taking notes. I was so inspired that I began taking notes the very next chapter. You can tell whe</span>
  <span id="freeText6503701414807458456" style="display:none">A book about books. A reading about readings. As a book-lover from a young age, I had only ever thought of reading as leisure and never as a discipline. I now see it as both—or, as Reinke puts it, a difficult pleasure. Who would have thought that there could be strategies to becoming a better reader? Not me! But Lit! contains some definitive, actionable tips. One chapter , for example, is devoted to taking notes. I was so inspired that I began taking notes the very next chapter. You can tell where in the book that chapter is located by looking at my paperback copy and noting where the mini Post-It! notes begin (I wasn’t convinced about writing on the pages of the book itself, but I did see the value on taking notes in some form closely linked to the physical book). Fantastic read!</span>
