<div id="review_490856726" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/490856726" />
    <a title="Elaine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/179330-elaine"><img alt="Elaine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571958404p2/179330.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/490856726?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elaine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elaine" href="/user/show/179330-elaine">Elaine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/179330-elaine?shelf=kindle">kindle</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer490856726" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4741666391653513944">I loved this book, but I have two regrets about it. My first regret is that I didn&apos;t buy it in paper, but instead read it on the Kindle. Although I did use the highlight feature, it isn&apos;t the same. This regret ties into my second regret...that I didn&apos;t read chapter 12 first. Chapter 12 is called Marginalia, all about writing in books. I have always loved to highlight and underline in my books, making the occasional note here and there, but he advocates carrying on a conversation with the author.</span>
  <span id="freeText4741666391653513944" style="display:none">I loved this book, but I have two regrets about it. My first regret is that I didn't buy it in paper, but instead read it on the Kindle. Although I did use the highlight feature, it isn't the same. This regret ties into my second regret...that I didn't read chapter 12 first. Chapter 12 is called Marginalia, all about writing in books. I have always loved to highlight and underline in my books, making the occasional note here and there, but he advocates carrying on a conversation with the author. It's quite fun to do and something I've enjoyed in other books since reading this one. <br /><br />I had many "take-aways' from this book, but one of the most practical and helpful was that it is OK to read just one chapter of a book. I've always been the perfectionist sort that wouldn't consider that I'd read a book unless I'd read every word in it. Now, when I wanted to study homemaking (which I did), I went and pulled out an assortment of books that had at least one chapter dedicated to the topic and just read those chapters. It was liberating and fun! I loved easily seeing how different authors treated the subject. And I made notes galore. <br /><br />The main thesis of the book is about Christians reading books...first the Bible then everything else. It deals with fiction and non-fiction books written by Christian and non-Christian authors. He gives great reasons for why Christians should read non-Christian authors and how to discern worldviews. <br /><br />Overall, this is a great book and one I will want my kids to read, I think when they are in high school. I wish I'd read it much sooner!</span>
  <a data-text-id="4741666391653513944" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


