<div id="review_310195403" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/310195403" />
    <a title="Bill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5784721-bill"><img alt="Bill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459820735p2/5784721.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/310195403?book_show_action=true">Apr 10, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bill" href="/user/show/5784721-bill">Bill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5784721-bill?shelf=books-about-books">books-about-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5784721-bill?shelf=theology">theology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5784721-bill?shelf=christian-life">christian-life</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer310195403" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5760729910877673719">Loved this book! Reading books about books always feels kind of indulgent, but this book by Tony Reinke is genuinely good. Given that I invest so much time in reading, and value it so highly, it really makes sense to think carefully about why I read, how I read and what I read, and &quot;Lit&quot; nails all those issues and more. The &quot;theology of books and reading&quot; in the first 6 chapters was enlightening and encouraging -- highlights being the biblical primacy of words over images, the importance of a bi</span>
  <span id="freeText5760729910877673719" style="display:none">Loved this book! Reading books about books always feels kind of indulgent, but this book by Tony Reinke is genuinely good. Given that I invest so much time in reading, and value it so highly, it really makes sense to think carefully about why I read, how I read and what I read, and "Lit" nails all those issues and more. The "theology of books and reading" in the first 6 chapters was enlightening and encouraging -- highlights being the biblical primacy of words over images, the importance of a biblical worldview as a foundation for reading and the case for reading non-Christian books. Part 2 ("Practical Advice on Book Reading") was even more enjoyable! Most influential has been his suggestion for how to plan your reading (I'm going to adopt the categories suggested), a few key suggestions on how to read non-fiction (Ask why you're reading a book with concrete questions to have answered, read rapidly and revisit thought provoking sections later, invest 30-60 minutes in analysing a book before you start it), his general encouragment to read more broadly, and finally the encouragement to write in books -- in pen!! We'll see how I go with that, but I have now given it a go, and my copy of Lit is thoroughly defaced!</span>
  <a data-text-id="5760729910877673719" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


